  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">International</h3>

  <p>According to the International Monetary Fund projections, global economic growth is expected to decline from 3.4% at the end of 2022 to 2.8% by the end of 2023. Nevertheless, despite the turbulence in the financial sector, a medium-term growth of 3% is anticipated, remaining resilient and avoiding a recession. </p>

  <p>Regarding Latin America and the Caribbean, the economic growth deceleration is expected to deepen, reaching a rate of 1.2%. The countries in the region continue to face limited space for fiscal and monetary policies. While inflation in the region shows a downward trend, the impact of restrictive policies on private consumption and investment will be more strongly felt throughout the year.  </p>

  <p>Globally, the first signs are emerging that the monetary policies implemented by central banks to combat prevailing inflationary pressures are starting to have an effect on economic activity. It is projected that by the end of 2023, the overall inflation rate will decrease from 8.7% in 2022 to 7.0%, driven by the lower price of raw materials. However, underlying inflation is likely to decrease at a slower pace. </p>

