  <h3 class="c-left c-font-lowercase c-font-sbold">National</h3>

  <p>According to the "Mexico Situation" report, prepared by BBVA Mexico, economic growth is expected to increase in 2023, now projecting a growth of 2.4%, compared to the previous 1.4%. This estimate is based on the good dynamism that the Mexican economy experienced during the first quarter of the year. It highlights the manufacturing sector, which has shown signs of normalization, driving a fast recovery in investment in machinery and equipment, especially in the imported component, which was 16.4% higher than its level in January 2019.  </p>

  <p>Despite the fact that the dynamism in the manufacturing sector has been remarkable, some segments of gross fixed investment, such as residential construction, still show a significant lag, registering a level 21.6% below that observed in January 2019. Nevertheless, estimates indicate that the Mexican economy will maintain a certain degree of strength despite the challenges that may arise in the global economic outlook.    </p>

  <p>It is anticipated that the Mexican economy will face a gradual deceleration towards the second half of 2023, stemming from the progressive weakening of durable goods demand in the U.S. However, it is expected that the resilience of domestic consumption will prevent a more pronounced decline in Mexico's Gross Domestic Product during this period of the year, bolstered by the accumulated income gains since the second half of the previous year. For the year 2024, a GDP growth of 1.8% is projected, partly due to the drag effect caused by the economic slowdown experienced at the end of the current year.    </p>


