  <p>According to data from the Government of Mexico, there is a housing deficit of over 9 million units in the country. However, the rising cost of construction materials and fuels has contributed to the scarcity of real estate offerings. Additionally, in line with the increased demand for labor due to nearshoring activities, coupled with the rise in global interest rates and the prevailing inflationary pressure in the U.S., which could potentially impact consumption and remittances, increases in housing prices are projected to be within a range of 8% to 10% during the year. </p>

  <p>Furthermore, the housing demand could increase during the upcoming periods, as a result of the higher provision of loans by INFONAVIT, following the launch of a new program called "Mujer Infonavit." This program aims to address the labor and social inequalities faced by women by reducing the required number of points to apply for a home loan or debt payment and extending the repayment period by five years. </p>

